   <refnamediv>
       <refname>ols0 </refname>
               <refpurpose>ordinary least squares </refpurpose>
   </refnamediv>
 
        <refsynopsisdiv>
               <title>CALLING SEQUENCE</title>
               <synopsis>[bhat,ixpx]=ols0(y,x)</synopsis>
        </refsynopsisdiv>
 
        <refsection>
           <title>PARAMETERS</title>
           <variablelist>
           <varlistentry>
 
           <term>Input</term>
 
<listitem><para>*  <term> y </term> =    dependent variable vector (nobs x 1)</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> x </term> =    independent variables matrix (nobs x nvar)</para></listitem>
 
 
 
<listitem><para>&#160;</para></listitem>
 
           </varlistentry>
 
          <varlistentry>
 
          <term>Output</term>
 
<listitem><para>*  <term> bhat </term> =    estimated beta in y  =   x*beta+u</para></listitem>
<listitem><para>*  <term> ixpx </term> =    inverse of matrix x'*x</para></listitem>
 
 
          </varlistentry>
          </variablelist>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>DESCRIPTION</title>
The most basic least-squares regression: provides only the estimated beta, bhat, and the inverse of matrix x'*x. Used mainly in other programs.
 
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>EXAMPLE</title>
              <programlisting role="example"><![CDATA[
x=grand(15,3,'nor',0,1)
y=x*ones(3,1)+grand(15,1,'nor',0,1)
b=ols0(y,x)
 
               ]]></programlisting>
        </refsection>
 
        <refsection>
               <title>AUTHOR</title>
Eric Dubois 2002
        </refsection>
</refentry>
